<!-- PHILOSOPHY -->
<div class="section section-alt">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div>
      <div class="section-eyebrow">My Philosophy</div>
      <h2>The best offense is a <em>good defense.</em></h2>
      <p class="body-text">I come to every project prepared. That means doing the research before the design, understanding the learner before writing the objectives, and anticipating the edge cases before launch.</p>
      <p class="body-text">At the same time, I've learned that the best-prepared designers are also the best at pivoting. Learner data, SME feedback, and classroom reality reshape every project. I stay ready to adapt without losing the thread of what the learning needs to do.</p>
      <blockquote class="philosophy-quote">"Chance favors only the prepared mind." — Louis Pasteur</blockquote>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- APPROACH -->
<div class="section">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-eyebrow">My Approach</div>
    <h2>I design like an architect and iterate like a <em>teacher.</em></h2>
    <p class="body-text">Every learning product I build starts with the same question: what should a learner be able to do that they couldn't do before? From there, I work backward, identifying the knowledge, skills, and practice opportunities needed to get there.</p>
    <div class="approach-grid">
      <div class="approach-card">
        <h3>Evidence-Based Design</h3>
        <p>My process integrates ADDIE and backward design with cognitive load theory, spaced practice, and retrieval-based learning. Good design is a craft grounded in research.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="approach-card">
        <h3>AI as Accelerator</h3>
        <p>I use AI to speed up assessment iteration, content modernization, gap analysis, and scalable revision cycles, all while keeping evidence-based pedagogy at the center. AI speeds the work, but principles determine what's worth building.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="approach-card">
        <h3>Built for Real Learners</h3>
        <p>I don't design for the ideal learner. I design for the full range, from diverse backgrounds, varied preparation, and real constraints.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

